content: Wow, works surprisingly well! Installation instructions could be more clear though. You need to 1) open up developer mode on your tablet, 2) allow "USB Debugging" in developer options on your tablet, 3) install a "Universal ADB driver" on your Windows computer, 4) install Twomon SE on your Windows computer from their website, 5) install Twomon SE app on your tablet here, 6) connect the two devices via USB, 7) explicitly allow "USB debugging" from your Windows computer on your tablet screen, then finally 8) open the apps on both devices and wait a moment for them to recognize each other. THEN then tablet just WORKS like any other second monitor! It's actually fairly straightforward once you understand the steps, but the instructions should be explained more clearly instead of spread out over multiple FAQ and support documents.
replyContent: Thank you for your review for our product. We will always try to improve the performance. if you have inquiry, please contact us through the website. we will be solve your inquiry. (Contact us : http://www.easynlight.com/en/contacttwomon/)

content: I've tried about a half dozen similar apps and they all disappointed me. This is the first one that worked exactly as I wanted. It sees me Samsung Galaxy Tab S5e with it's native resolution of 2560x1600. I use a scaling of 250% and it looks great. Other apps always used standard display resolutions that didn't match the tablet. That resulted in jagged text and poor graphics. No such issues with Twomon SE. I use a single USB C cable and my tablet even stays charged off my laptop. The performance is not quite as fast as an HDMI monitor, but it works great for documents and web browsing. It also uses a lot less CPU on the laptop than many other similar apps. This was a lot less expensive than buying an external USB C monitor and saves weight in my bag. For a frequent traveler, that is a big deal. I cannot say enough good things about this app.

content: This is an amazing app, that enabled me to put decommisioned Nvidia Shield Tablet as a helper screen. The latency and the overall quality is great taking in account that it works over USB debugging.   It auto reconnects when tablet is put to sleep with Android Debugging Interface via AutoHotkey script and contunies to run in background so there are no interruptions. This feature can also be integrated in to program, to sleep with a hotkey or while the computer screen sleeps because it is already utilizing Android Debugging Interface.  There is a small bug where I select the full resolution of 1920x1200 of the external tablet the touch control is not responsive and targets to different points of screen instead of the intended location like when you click the scroll bar, it opens the date and time menu in taskbar. So I am forced to use a loser resolution which makes the overall responsive better with a little trade of to the image quality.

content: Works simply, although depending on your use case, there are a few issues: 1- There is an option to scale the display to full screen on the tablet, but it doesn't work, at least for me on a Pixel C. So, if strictly want to use your tablet as a monitor, and not for input, it works quite well.  Not great for input, though.
